There‚Äôs a Bloodborne dash replacement for the roll made for Dark Souls 3 and one for Elden Ring by the same guy for people on PC.  It suits the style of combat for both games very well since both are like Bloodborne with a Dark Souls guy dropped in.  Square peg, round hole.

Just because it‚Äôs meant to be hard doesn‚Äôt mean everything that makes it hard improves the enjoyment of the game or contributes to the Soulsborne philosophy.  And the tedious, annoying things can jump off a cliff.  Speaking of, I‚Äôve always thought losing souls/echoes/runes on death was dumb.  Usually it‚Äôs just an annoying amount of time to go back and retrieve it or get the stuff back by killing for a longer way.  So it‚Äôs annoying, not challenging or difficult.  But, the Soulsborne games are all about overcoming with persistence.  So, getting closer and closer to leveling or getting items each time you fail, i.e. keeping your resource, would be in line with that while losing them is against.  That‚Äôs dumb.

Elden Ring's combat system is abysmal.  It's copy/pasted from Dark Souls 1 which is more than a decade old now.  The combat is slow, disconnected, laggy, unresponsive, and the mobs are absolute cheese-tier.  Mobs track you, read your inputs, and will instantly turn 180 degrees even if you've dodged their attacks, and still hit you.  Other than the pretty world, Elden Ring is a complete mess.  I give it 2 out of 5.

Quick comment about the inflation. The price of the product is not what matters only, it is the relation between your salary that it matters. Yes with the inflation that 20 dollar game is like 120 today BUT what matters more is how much of your salary back then was that 20 dollars because e.g if you had 500 dollars per month and a video game was 20 dollars then it was 1/25 of your salary and if today you have 1000 dollars per month and a video game is 60 dollars then it is 1/16.66 of your salary making it 1.5 times more expensive today than back then.

Translating the prices from them to now, without doing the same to the salary, gives only half the information. As a non American person I do not know what the average salary was back then or even today for a person in the US but both sides must be accounted for in order to show how expensive is something relatively to your salary and not as just a price tag alone.

Sweet human progress! :O I remember seeing this review back in the day, but I never really thought to actively go try the game out (having not gamed much in recent years, t'all).  But WOW.  Steam had it as free to try for a few days (and only $6 for purchase after that), and I was instantly hooked.  While the game's concept and design are SO incredibly simple, and quite likely just a slight deviation on other existing phone app dungeon crawlers that I've played off and on for years.......it is a masterpiece, no question.  Anything it may have evolved from it has effectively perfected.  Even only being about 5 hrs into gameplay now (and wow, already such a HUGE difference in my skill level) I give this game EASILY an 8.5/10.  Granted, I review it on the basis of its intent and genre: is it gonna have the same level of complexity, graphics, time put in by developers, etc as something like Breath of the Wild?  Obviously not, but it's not trying to be that.  For it's genre, it deserves an 8.5, maybe even 9, out of 10.

I think, in closing, what has to be, by FAR, my favorite element of the game?........you don't directly progress further by just sinking hours into grinding, and you CERTAINLY don't have the option to "pay to win".  No, with "Enter the Gungeon", your success is measured by your skill level -both one's general, meta gaming talents, as well as specific familiarity with this game's mechanics.  There IS no "grind mindlessly" or "burn your $" options to win; if you want to win, you have to BE GOOD.   And that is something SO horrifyingly lost in practically all video games in the modern age: you don't have to demonstrate or gain actual talent or skill to win.  WELL, NOT IN "Enter the Gungeon" üòÉüëç

This has to be quite literally the most beautiful pieces of art I ever seen In many ways, the work of a critic is easy. We risk very little, yet enjoy a position over those who offer up their work and their selves to our judgment. We thrive on negative criticism, which is fun to write and to read. But the bitter truth we critics must face, is that in the grand scheme of things, the average piece of junk is probably more meaningful than our criticism designating it so. But there are times when a critic truly risks something, and that is in the discovery and defense of the *new*. The world is often unkind to new talent, new creations. The new needs friends. Last night, I experienced something new: an extraordinary video from a singularly unexpected source. To say that both the video and its maker have challenged my preconceptions about fine Video Editing is a gross understatement. They have rocked me to my core. In the past, I have made no secret of my disdain for this channel and it‚Äôs famous motto, "Anyone can make a YouTube Video" But I realize, only now do I truly understand what they meant. Not everyone can become a great artist; but a great artist *can* come from *anywhere*. It is difficult to imagine more humble origins than those of the genius now making videos on this channel, who is, in this critic's opinion, nothing less than the finest YouTuber in France. I will be returning to this channel soon, hungry for more.

I'm 22 and have ADHD, been off my medication for almost 2 years and have been looking for alternatives as I head back into college. I've been trying a variety of these high caffeine coffees, and I intend to give this black label a try, but even brands with a lower dosage give me an adequate buzz. The biohazard brand is around 900mg and for about an hour I feel like I'm on an adderall 10mg. I think my ADHD is a variable in how I experience coffee however as I frequently hear from other people that coffee doesn't have much an effect on them. I've thought about various ways to put what ADHD feels like into words, in terms of integers it feels like this: -1/0/+1 where zero is your mind at homeostasis and -1 is your mind with ADHD. With ADHD your mind is at -1 24/7, a normal person is at 0, and +1 represents high motivation/concentration. A person that is normally at 0 while at rest should have no problem getting to +1 even without taking a stimulus, but for someone that's always at -1, it is much more difficult getting to 0 much less getting to +1. Personally at -1 my thought process feels foggy, and the mental fatigue from various tasks whether it be studying or housework sets in MUCH quicker than it would with someone at 0 or +1, what ends up happening is my mind starts searching for anything even slightly more interesting to focus my attention, sometimes it doesn't even have to be visual, it can be a random thought, and suddenly that single thought takes your mind off on a tangent and you've completely zoned out of whatever you were concentrating on just prior. At 0 or +1 that's technically still possible, but it would take a little longer. The coffee I had brings me to about .25 to .5, so slightly above 0 but not quite 1, however even then I feel much more concentrated and willing to study/work than I am at -1. I wish people could understand the difference between even -1 and 0 is major, if I were approached by a magic genie and told my mind could return to 0 indefinitely at the consequence of never reaching +1, I'd still take that offer, 0 is still much much better than -1.
